# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: anaphora-linguistics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] An outcome of ambiguity is uncertainty, but uncertainty itself refers to a state in which outcomes or meanings are known but their likelihood, stability, or implications cannot be reliably assessed.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Ambiguity is not simply the absence of information.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] It is the lack of meaning and direction caused by insufficient context and unclear framing, which obstructs the ability to determine what counts as a valid interpretation or resolution.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] The prefix ambi- reflects the idea of “two” or “multiple,” as in multiple possible meanings.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] The concept of ambiguity is generally contrasted with vagueness.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] In ambiguity, multiple distinct interpretations compete because the frame of meaning is unclear and is shaped by personal history and mental models.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] With vagueness, in contrast, the general interpretation is often understood, but the boundaries are fuzzy, so it is difficult to specify the meaning at the desired level of precision.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Lexical ambiguity is contrasted with semantic ambiguity.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] The former represents a choice between a finite number of known and meaningful context-dependent interpretations.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] The latter represents a choice between any number of possible interpretations, none of which may have a standard agreed-upon meaning.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] This form of ambiguity is closely related to vagueness.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Ambiguity in human language is argued to reflect principles of efficient communication.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Languages that communicate efficiently will avoid sending information that is redundant with information provided in the context.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] This can be shown mathematically to result in a system that is ambiguous when context is neglected.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] In this way, ambiguity is viewed as a generally useful feature of a linguistic system.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Linguistic ambiguity can be a problem in law, because the interpretation of written documents and oral agreements is often of paramount importance.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] The lexical ambiguity of a word or phrase applies to it having more than one meaning in the language to which the word belongs.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] "Meaning" here refers to whatever should be represented by a good dictionary.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] For instance, the word "bank" has several distinct lexical definitions, including "financial institution" and "edge of a river".
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] One could say, "I bought herbs from the apothecary".
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] This could mean one actually spoke to the apothecary (pharmacist) or went to the apothecary (pharmacy).
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] The context in which an ambiguous word is used often makes it clearer which of the meanings is intended.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] If, for instance, someone says, "I put $100 in the bank", most people would not think someone used a shovel to dig in the mud.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] However, some linguistic contexts do not provide sufficient information to make a used word clearer.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Lexical ambiguity can be addressed by algorithmic methods that automatically associate the appropriate meaning with a word in context, a task referred to as word-sense disambiguation.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] The use of multi-defined words requires the author or speaker to clarify their context and sometimes elaborate on their specific intended meaning (in which case, a less ambiguous term should have been used).
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] The goal of clear, concise communication is that the receiver(s) have no misunderstanding about what was meant to be conveyed.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] An exception to this could include a politician whose "weasel words" and obfuscation are necessary to gain support from multiple constituents with mutually exclusive conflicting desires from their candidate of choice.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Ambiguity is a powerful tool of political science.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] More problematic are words whose multiple meanings express closely related concepts.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] "Good", for example, can mean "useful" or "functional" (*That's a good hammer*), "exemplary" (*She's a good student*), "pleasing" (*This is good soup*), "moral" (*a good person* versus *the lesson to be learned from a story*), "righteous", etc.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] "I have a good daughter" is not clear about which sense is intended.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] The various ways to apply prefixes and suffixes can also create ambiguity ("unlockable" can mean "capable of being opened" or "impossible to lock").
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Semantic ambiguity occurs when a word, phrase, or sentence has more than one possible interpretation.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] 2. an action the woman performed (verb phrase with *duck* as a verb and *her* as the object of *saw*).
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] "We saw her duck" contains syntactic ambiguity in addition to semantic ambiguity.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Syntactic ambiguity arises when a sentence can have different meanings because of the structure of the sentence, or syntax.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] This is often due to a modifying expression, such as a prepositional phrase, the application of which is unclear.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] For example, the sentence "He ate the cookies on the couch" could mean that he ate the cookies that were on the couch (as opposed to those that were on the table), or it could mean that he was sitting on the couch when he ate the cookies.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Only rewriting the sentence or placing appropriate punctuation can resolve a syntactic ambiguity.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] For syntactic ambiguity in formal languages (such as computer programming languages), see ambiguous grammar.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Conversely, a sentence like "He ate the cookies on the couch" is also semantically ambiguous.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Rarely, but occasionally, the different parsings of a syntactically ambiguous phrase result in the same meaning.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Spoken language can contain many more types of ambiguities that are called phonological ambiguities, where there is more than one way to compose a set of sounds into words, such as "ice cream" and "I scream".
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Such ambiguity is generally resolved according to the context.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] A mishearing of such, based on incorrectly resolved ambiguity, is called a mondegreen.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Philosophers (and other users of logic) spend a lot of time and effort searching for and removing (or intentionally adding) ambiguity in arguments because it can lead to incorrect conclusions and can be used to deliberately conceal bad arguments.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] For example, a politician might say, "I oppose taxes which hinder economic growth", an example of a glittering generality.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Some will think they oppose taxes in general because they hinder economic growth.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Others may think they oppose only those taxes that they believe will hinder economic growth.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] In writing, the sentence can be rewritten to reduce possible misinterpretation, either by adding a comma after "taxes" (to convey the first sense), or by changing "which" to "that" (to convey the second sense), or by rewriting it in other ways.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] The devious politician hopes that each constituent will interpret the statement in the most desirable way, and think the politician supports everyone's opinion.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] However, the opposite can also be true—an opponent can turn a positive statement into a bad one if the speaker uses ambiguity (intentionally or not).
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] The logical fallacies of amphiboly and equivocation rely heavily on the use of ambiguous words and phrases.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] In continental philosophy (particularly phenomenology and existentialism), there is much greater tolerance of ambiguity, as it is generally seen as an integral part of the human condition.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Martin Heidegger argued that the relation between the subject and object is ambiguous, as is the relation of mind and body and part and whole.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] In Heidegger's phenomenology, Dasein is always in a meaningful world, but there is always an underlying background for every instance of signification.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Thus, although some things may be certain, they have little to do with Dasein's sense of care and existential anxiety, e.g., in the face of death.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] In calling his work Being and Nothingness an "essay in phenomenological ontology" Jean-Paul Sartre follows Heidegger in defining the human essence as ambiguous, or relating fundamentally to such ambiguity.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Ethics cannot be based on the authoritative certainty given by mathematics and logic, or prescribed directly from the empirical findings of science.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] She states: "Since we do not succeed in fleeing it, let us, therefore, try to look the truth in the face.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Let us try to assume our fundamental ambiguity.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] It is in the knowledge of the genuine conditions of our life that we must draw our strength to live and our reason for acting".
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] In literature and rhetoric, ambiguity can be a useful tool.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Groucho Marx's classic joke depends on a grammatical ambiguity for its humor, for example: "Last night I shot an elephant in my pajamas.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] How he got in my pajamas, I'll never know".
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Songs and poetry often rely on ambiguous words for artistic effect, as in the song title "Don't It Make My Brown Eyes Blue" (where "blue" can refer to the color or to sadness).
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] In the narrative, ambiguity can be introduced in several ways: motive, plot, and character.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Scott Fitzgerald uses the latter type of ambiguity with notable effect in his novel *The Great Gatsby*.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Mathematical notation is a helpful tool that eliminates a lot of misunderstandings associated with natural language in physics and other sciences.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Nonetheless, there are still some inherent ambiguities due to lexical, syntactic, and semantic reasons that persist in mathematical notation.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] The ambiguity in the style of writing a function should not be confused with a multivalued function, which can (and should) be defined in a deterministic and unambiguous way.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Several special functions still do not have established notations.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Usually, the conversion to another notation requires scaling the argument or the resulting value; sometimes, the same name of the function is used, causing confusion.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Ambiguous expressions often appear in physical and mathematical texts.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] It is common practice to omit multiplication signs in mathematical expressions.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Also, it is common to give the same name to a variable and a function, for example, $f=f(x)$ .
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Then, if one sees $f=f(y+1)$ , there is no way to distinguish whether it means $f=f(x)$ **multiplied** by $(y+1)$ , or function f **evaluated** at argument equal to $(y+1)$ .
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] In each case of use of such notations, the reader is supposed to be able to perform the deduction and reveal the true meaning.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Creators of algorithmic languages try to avoid ambiguities.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Many algorithmic languages (C++ and Fortran) require the character * as a symbol of multiplication.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] The Wolfram Language used in Mathematica allows the user to omit the multiplication symbol but requires square brackets to indicate the argument of a function; square brackets are not allowed for grouping of expressions.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Fortran, in addition, does not allow the use of the same name (identifier) for different objects, for example, a function and a variable; in particular, the expression $f=f(x)$ is qualified as an error.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] The order of operations may depend on the context.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] In most programming languages, the operations of division and multiplication have equal priority and are executed from left to right.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Until the last century, many editorials assumed that multiplication is performed first, for example, $a/bc$ is interpreted as $a/(bc)$ ; in this case, the insertion of parentheses is required when translating the formulas to an algorithmic language.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] In addition, it is common to write an argument of a function without parentheses, which also may lead to ambiguity.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] In the scientific journal style, one uses Roman letters to denote elementary functions, whereas variables are written using italics.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] For example, in mathematical journals the expression $sin$ does not denote the sine function but the product of the three variables s , i , n , although in the informal notation of a slide presentation it may stand for $\sin$ .
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Commas in multi-component subscripts and superscripts are sometimes omitted; this is also potentially ambiguous notation.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] For example, in the notation $T_{mnk}$ , the reader can only infer from the context whether it means a single-index object, taken with the subscript equal to the product of variables m , n and k , or it is an indication of a trivalent tensor.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Often the author's intention can be understood from the context, in cases where only one of the two makes sense, but an ambiguity like this should be avoided, for example by writing $\sin ^{2}(\alpha /2)$ or ${\textstyle {\frac {1}{2}}\sin ^{2}\alpha }$ .
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] The expression $\sin ^{-1}\alpha$ means $\arcsin(\alpha )$ in several texts, though it might be thought to mean $(\sin \alpha )^{-1}$ , since $\sin ^{n}\alpha$ commonly means $(\sin \alpha )^{n}$ .
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Conversely, $\sin ^{2}\alpha$ might seem to mean $\sin(\sin \alpha )$ , as this exponentiation notation usually denotes function iteration: in general, $f^{2}(x)$ means $f(f(x))$ .
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] However, for trigonometric and hyperbolic functions, this notation conventionally means exponentiation of the result of function application.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] The expression $a/2b$ can be interpreted as meaning $(a/2)b$ ; however, it is more commonly understood to mean $a/(2b)$ .
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] It is common to define the coherent states in quantum optics with $~|\alpha \rangle ~$ and states with a fixed number of photons with $~|n\rangle ~$ .
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Then, there is an "unwritten rule": the state is coherent if there are more Greek characters than Latin characters in the argument and n -photon state if the Latin characters dominate.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] The ambiguity becomes even worse, if $~|x\rangle ~$ is used for the states with a certain value of the coordinate and $~|p\rangle ~$ means the state with a certain value of the momentum, which may be used in books on quantum mechanics.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Such ambiguities easily lead to confusions, especially if some normalized adimensional, dimensionless variables are used.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Expression $|1\rangle$ may mean a state with a single photon, or the coherent state with mean amplitude equal to 1, or state with momentum equal to unity, and so on.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] The reader is supposed to guess from the context.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Some physical quantities do not yet have established notations; their value (and sometimes even dimension, as in the case of the Einstein coefficients) depends on the system of notations.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Each use of an ambiguous term should be preceded by the definition suitable for a specific case.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Just like Ludwig Wittgenstein states in Tractatus Logico-Philosophicus: "...
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] For example, the sentence "the gain of a system should be doubled", without context, means close to nothing.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] The term *intensity* is ambiguous when applied to light.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] The term can refer to any of irradiance, luminous intensity, radiant intensity, or radiance, depending on the background of the person using the term.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Also, confusions may be related to the use of atomic percent as a measure of concentration of a dopant or resolution of an imaging system as a measure of the size of the smallest detail that can be resolved at the background of statistical noise.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] The Berry paradox arises as a result of systematic ambiguity in the meaning of terms such as "definable" or "nameable".
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Terms of this kind give rise to vicious circle fallacies.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Other terms with this type of ambiguity are: satisfiable, true, false, function, property, class, relation, cardinal, and ordinal.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Logical ambiguity and self-contradiction are analogous to visual ambiguity and impossible objects, such as the Necker cube and impossible cube, or many of the drawings of M.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Ambiguity in the social sciences refers to situations, meanings, identities, or social arrangements that resist clear classification or stable interpretation.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Rather than viewing ambiguity as a problem to be resolved, scholars examine how uncertainty, indeterminacy, and multiplicity are actively lived, negotiated, and sometimes strategically maintained in social life.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Across anthropology, sociology, and political theory, ambiguity has been used to analyse crisis, governance, moral reasoning, and social change, highlighting how people navigate competing norms, values, and futures.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Attention to ambiguity foregrounds lived experience, affect, and power, showing how social actors make sense of complex worlds where outcomes, roles, and meanings remain unsettled.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Social scientists note that ambiguity has been examined or investigated across many disciplines concerned with knowledge and knowledge production, including mathematics, philosophy, logic, and the natural, behavioural, and social sciences.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] They show that these fields have variously treated ambiguity as something to control, resolve, or strategically use.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] In anthropology, early efforts to define and classify social and cultural life were similarly shaped by ambiguity, as categories were often marked by exceptions, contradictions, and overlap.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Foundational studies of boundaries—such as those between the sacred and profane, purity and pollution, and myth and meaning—demonstrated how social order operates despite continual flux and indeterminacy.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Some languages have been created with the intention of avoiding ambiguity, especially lexical ambiguity.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Lojban and Loglan are two related languages that have been created for this, focusing chiefly on syntactic ambiguity.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] The languages can be both spoken and written.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] These languages are intended to provide greater technical precision over natural languages, although historically, such attempts at language improvement have been criticized.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Languages composed from many diverse sources contain much ambiguity and inconsistency.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] The many exceptions to syntax and semantic rules are time-consuming and difficult to learn.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] In structural biology, ambiguity has been recognized as a problem for studying protein conformations.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] The analysis of a protein's three-dimensional structure consists in dividing the macromolecule into subunits called domains.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] The difficulty of this task arises from the fact that different definitions of what a domain is can be used (e.g., folding autonomy, function, thermodynamic stability, or domain motions), which sometimes results in a single protein having different—yet equally valid—domain assignments.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Christianity and Judaism employ the concept of paradox synonymously with "ambiguity".
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Many Christians and Jews endorse Rudolf Otto's description of the sacred as 'mysterium tremendum et fascinans,' the awe-inspiring mystery that fascinates humans.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Chesterton regularly employed paradox to tease out the meanings in common concepts that he found ambiguous or to reveal meaning often overlooked or forgotten in common phrases: the title of one of his most famous books, *Orthodoxy* (1908), itself employed such a paradox.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] In music, pieces or sections that confound expectations and may be, or are, interpreted simultaneously in different ways are ambiguous.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Examples being some polytonality, polymeter, other ambiguous meters or rhythms, and ambiguous phrasing, or (Stein 2005, p.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] The music of Africa is often purposely ambiguous .
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] To quote Sir Donald Francis Tovey (1935, p.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] In visual art, certain images are visually ambiguous, such as the Necker cube, which can be interpreted in two ways.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Perceptions of such objects remain stable for a time, then may flip, a phenomenon called multistable perception.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] The opposite of such ambiguous images are impossible objects.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] In social psychology, ambiguity is a factor used in determining people's responses to various situations.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] High levels of ambiguity in an emergency (e.g., an unconscious man lying on a park bench) make witnesses less likely to offer any sort of assistance, due to the fear that they may have misinterpreted the situation and acted unnecessarily.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] Alternately, non-ambiguous emergencies (e.g., an injured person verbally asking for help) elicit more consistent intervention and assistance.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] With regard to the bystander effect, studies have shown that emergencies deemed ambiguous trigger the appearance of the classic bystander effect (wherein more witnesses decrease the likelihood of them helping) far more than non-ambiguous emergencies.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] In computer science, the SI prefixes *kilo-*, *mega-*, and *giga-* were historically used in certain contexts to mean either the first three powers of 1024 (1024, 10242, and 10243), contrary to the metric system, in which these units unambiguously mean one thousand, one million, and one billion.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] This usage is particularly prevalent with electronic memory devices (e.g., DRAM) addressed directly by a binary machine register where a decimal interpretation makes no practical sense.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] 1 M (where M is ambiguously 1000000 or 1048576) is *less* uncertain than the engineering value 1.0×106 (defined to designate the interval 950000 to 1050000).
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ambiguity] As non-volatile storage devices begin to exceed 1 GB in capacity (where the ambiguity begins to routinely impact the second significant digit), GB and TB almost always mean 109 and 1012 bytes.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] In linguistics, **anaphora** (/əˈnæfərə, -frə/) is the use of an expression whose interpretation depends upon another expression in context (its antecedent).
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] In a narrower sense, anaphora is the use of an expression that depends specifically upon an antecedent expression and thus is contrasted with cataphora, which is the use of an expression that depends upon a postcedent expression.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] The anaphoric (referring) term is called an **anaphor**.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] For example, in the sentence *Sally arrived, but nobody saw her*, the pronoun *her* is an anaphor, referring back to the antecedent *Sally*.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] In the sentence *Before her arrival, nobody saw Sally*, the pronoun *her* refers forward to the postcedent *Sally*, so *her* is now a cataphor (and an anaphor in the broader sense, but not in the narrower one).
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] Usually, an anaphoric expression is a pro-form or some other kind of deictic (contextually dependent) expression.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] Both anaphora and cataphora are species of endophora, referring to something mentioned elsewhere in a dialog or text.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] The term *anaphora* is actually used in two ways.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] In a broad sense, it denotes the act of referring.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] Any time a given expression (e.g. a pro-form) refers to another contextual entity, anaphora is present.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] In a second, narrower sense, the term *anaphora* denotes the act of referring backwards in a dialog or text, such as referring to the left when an anaphor points to its left toward its antecedent in languages that are written from left to right.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] Etymologically, *anaphora* derives from Ancient Greek ἀναφορά (*anaphorá*, 'a carrying back'), from ἀνά (*aná*, 'up') + φέρω (*phérō*, 'I carry').
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] A pro-form is a cataphor when it points to its right toward its postcedent.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] Both effects together are called either anaphora (broad sense) or less ambiguously, along with self-reference they comprise the category of endophora.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] Examples of anaphora (in the narrow sense) and cataphora are given next.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] A further distinction is drawn between endophoric and exophoric reference.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] Exophoric reference occurs when an expression, an exophor, refers to something that is not directly present in the linguistic context, but is rather present in the situational context.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] Deictic pro-forms are stereotypical exophors, e.g.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] are exophors; they point to entities in the situational context.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] is an exophor; it points to a location in the situational context.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] A listener might, for example, realize through listening to other clauses and sentences that *she* is *a Queen* because of some of her attributes or actions mentioned.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] Homophoric reference occurs when a generic phrase obtains a specific meaning through knowledge of its context.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] For example, the referent of the phrase *the Queen* (using an emphatic definite article, not the less specific *a Queen*, but also not the more specific *Queen Elizabeth*) must be determined by the context of the utterance, which would identify the identity of the queen in question.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] The term *anaphor* is used in a special way in the generative grammar tradition.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] Here it denotes what would normally be called a reflexive or reciprocal pronoun, such as *himself* or *each other* in English, and analogous forms in other languages.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] The use of the term *anaphor* in this narrow sense is unique to generative grammar, and in particular, to the traditional binding theory.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] This theory investigates the syntactic relationship that can or must hold between a given pro-form and its antecedent (or postcedent).
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] In this respect, anaphors (reflexive and reciprocal pronouns) behave very differently from, for instance, personal pronouns.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] In some cases, anaphora may refer not to its usual antecedent, but to its complement set.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] In the following example a, the anaphoric pronoun *they* refers to the children who are eating the ice-cream.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] In its narrower definition, an anaphoric pronoun must refer to some noun (phrase) that has already been introduced into the discourse.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] In complement anaphora cases, however, the anaphor refers to something that is not yet present in the discourse, since the pronoun's referent has not been formerly introduced, including the case of 'everything but' what has been introduced.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] The set of ice-cream-eating-children in example b is introduced into the discourse, but then the pronoun *they* refers to the set of non-ice-cream-eating-children, a set which has not been explicitly mentioned.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] The various possible referents in complement anaphora are discussed by Corblin (1996), Kibble (1997), and Nouwen (2003).
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] Resolving complement anaphora is of interest in shedding light on brain access to information, calculation, mental modeling, communication.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] There are many theories that attempt to prove how anaphors are related and trace back to their antecedents, with centering theory (Grosz, Joshi, and Weinstein 1983) being one of them.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] Taking the computational theory of mind view of language, centering theory gives a computational analysis of underlying antecedents.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] In their original theory, Grosz, Joshi, & Weinstein (1983) propose that some discourse entities in utterances are more "central" than others, and this degree of centrality imposes constraints on what can be the antecedent.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] In the theory, there are different types of centers: forward facing, backwards facing, and preferred.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] A ranked list of discourse entities in an utterance.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] The ranking is debated, some focusing on theta relations (Yıldırım et al.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] 2004) and some providing definitive lists.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] The highest ranked discourse entity in the previous utterance.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/anaphora-linguistics] The highest ranked discourse entity in the previous utterance realised in the current utterance.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek was the language of Homer and of fifth-century Athenian historians, playwrights, and philosophers.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] It has contributed many words to English vocabulary and has been a standard subject of study in educational institutions of the Western world since the Renaissance.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] This article primarily contains information about the Epic and Classical periods of the language, which are the best-attested periods and considered most typical of Ancient Greek.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek comprised several dialects, such as Attic, Ionic, Doric, Aeolic, and Arcadocypriot; among them, Attic Greek became the basis of Koine Greek.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Just like Koine is often included in Ancient Greek, conversely, Mycenaean Greek is usually treated separately and not always included in Ancient Greek – reflecting the fact that Greek in the first millennium BC is considered prototypical of Ancient Greek.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek was a pluricentric language, divided into many dialects.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] The main dialect groups are Attic and Ionic, Aeolic, Arcadocypriot, and Doric, many of them with several subdivisions.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Some dialects are found in standardized literary forms in literature, while others are attested only in inscriptions.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] There are also several historical forms.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Homeric Greek is a literary form of Archaic Greek (derived primarily from Ionic and Aeolic) used in the epic poems, the *Iliad* and the *Odyssey*, and in later poems by other authors.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Homeric Greek had significant differences in grammar and pronunciation from Classical Attic and other Classical-era dialects.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] The origins, early form and development of the Hellenic language family are not well understood because of a lack of contemporaneous evidence.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Several theories exist about what Hellenic dialect groups may have existed between the divergence of early Greek-like speech from the common Proto-Indo-European language and the Classical period.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] They have the same general outline but differ in some of the detail.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] The only attested dialect from this period is Mycenaean Greek, but its relationship to the historical dialects and the historical circumstances of the times imply that the overall groups already existed in some form.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Scholars assume that major Ancient Greek period dialect groups developed no later than 1120 BC, at the time of the Dorian invasions—and that their first appearances as precise alphabetic writing began in the 8th century BC.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] The invasion would not be "Dorian" unless the invaders had some cultural relationship to the historical Dorians.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] The invasion is known to have displaced population to the later Attic-Ionic regions, who regarded themselves as descendants of the population displaced by or contending with the Dorians.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] The Greeks of this period believed there were three major divisions of all Greek people – Dorians, Aeolians, and Ionians (including Athenians), each with their own defining and distinctive dialects.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Allowing for their oversight of Arcadian, an obscure mountain dialect, and Cypriot, far from the center of Greek scholarship, this division of people and language is quite similar to the results of modern archaeological-linguistic investigation.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] (Southern Italy and Sicily) in the classical period.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] West vs. non-West Greek is the strongest-marked and earliest division, with non-West in subsets of Ionic-Attic (or Attic-Ionic) and Aeolic vs.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Arcadocypriot, or Aeolic and Arcado-Cypriot vs.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Arcadocypriot apparently descended more closely from the Mycenaean Greek of the Bronze Age.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Boeotian Greek had come under a strong Northwest Greek influence, and can in some respects be considered a transitional dialect, as exemplified in the poems of the Boeotian poet Pindar who wrote in Doric with a small Aeolic admixture.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Thessalian likewise had come under Northwest Greek influence, though to a lesser degree.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Pamphylian Greek, spoken in a small area on the southwestern coast of Anatolia and little preserved in inscriptions, may be either a fifth major dialect group, or it is Mycenaean Greek overlaid by Doric, with a non-Greek native influence.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Based on the conclusions drawn by several studies and findings such as Pella curse tablet, Emilio Crespo and most scholars suggest that ancient Macedonian was a Northwest Doric dialect, which shares isoglosses with its neighboring Thessalian dialects spoken in northeastern Thessaly.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Some have also suggested an Aeolic Greek classification.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] For example, fragments of the works of the poet Sappho from the island of Lesbos are in Aeolian.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Most of the dialect sub-groups listed above had further subdivisions, generally equivalent to a city-state and its surrounding territory, or to an island.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Doric notably had several intermediate divisions as well, into Island Doric (including Cretan Doric), Southern Peloponnesus Doric (including Laconian, the dialect of Sparta), and Northern Peloponnesus Doric (including Corinthian).
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] All the groups were represented by colonies beyond Greece proper as well, and these colonies generally developed local characteristics, often under the influence of settlers or neighbors speaking different Greek dialects.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] After the conquests of Alexander the Great in the late 4th century BC, a new international dialect known as Koine or Common Greek developed, largely based on Attic Greek, but with influence from other dialects.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] This dialect slowly replaced most of the older dialects, although the Doric dialect has survived in the Tsakonian language, which is spoken in the region of modern Sparta.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Doric has also passed down its aorist terminations into most verbs of Demotic Greek.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] By about the 6th century AD, the Koine had slowly metamorphosed into Medieval Greek.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Phrygian is an extinct Indo-European language of West and Central Anatolia, which is regarded by current consensus to have been closely related to Greek.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Among Indo-European branches with living descendants, Greek is often argued to have the closest genetic ties with Armenian (see also Graeco-Armenian) and Indo-Iranian languages (see Graeco-Aryan).
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek differs from Proto-Indo-European (PIE) and other Indo-European languages in certain ways.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] In phonotactics, ancient Greek words could end only in a vowel or /n s r/; final stops were lost, as in γάλα "milk", compared with γάλακτος "of milk" (genitive).
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] The pronunciation of Ancient Greek was very different from that of Modern Greek.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek had long and short vowels; many diphthongs; double and single consonants; voiced, voiceless, and aspirated stops; and a pitch accent.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] In Modern Greek, all vowels and consonants are short.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Many vowels and diphthongs once pronounced distinctly are pronounced as /i/ (iotacism).
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Some of the stops and glides in diphthongs have become fricatives, and the pitch accent has changed to a stress accent.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Many of the changes took place in the Koine Greek period.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] The writing system of Modern Greek, however, does not reflect all pronunciation changes.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] The examples below represent Attic Greek in the 5th century BC.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Ancient pronunciation cannot be reconstructed with certainty, but Greek from the period is well documented, and there is little disagreement among linguists as to the general nature of the sounds that the letters represent.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] /oː/ raised to [uː], probably by the 4th century BC.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Greek, like all of the older Indo-European languages, is highly inflected.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] It is highly archaic in its preservation of Proto-Indo-European forms.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] In ancient Greek, nouns (including proper nouns) have five cases (nominative, genitive, dative, accusative, and vocative), three genders (masculine, feminine, and neuter), and three numbers (singular, dual, and plural).
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Verbs have four moods (indicative, imperative, subjunctive, and optative) and three voices (active, middle, and passive), as well as three persons (first, second, and third) and various other forms.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Verbs are conjugated through seven combinations of tenses and aspect (generally simply called "tenses"): the present, future, and imperfect are imperfective in aspect; the aorist, present perfect, pluperfect and future perfect are perfective in aspect.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Most tenses display all four moods and three voices, although there is no future subjunctive or imperative.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Also, there is no imperfect subjunctive, optative or imperative.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] The infinitives and participles correspond to the finite combinations of tense, aspect, and voice.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] The indicative of past tenses adds (conceptually, at least) a prefix /e-/, called the augment.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] This was probably originally a separate word, meaning something like "then", added because tenses in PIE had primarily aspectual meaning.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] The augment is added to the indicative of the aorist, imperfect, and pluperfect, but not to any of the other forms of the aorist (no other forms of the imperfect and pluperfect exist).
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] The two kinds of augment in Greek are syllabic and quantitative.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] The syllabic augment is added to stems beginning with consonants, and simply prefixes *e* (stems beginning with *r*, however, add *er*).
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Some verbs augment irregularly; the most common variation is *e* → *ei*.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] The irregularity can be explained diachronically by the loss of *s* between vowels, or that of the letter *w*, which affected the augment when it was word-initial.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] In verbs with a preposition as a prefix, the augment is placed not at the start of the word, but between the preposition and the original verb.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] For example, προσ(-)βάλλω (I attack) goes to προσ**έ**βαλoν in the aorist.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] However compound verbs consisting of a prefix that is not a preposition retain the augment at the start of the word: αὐτο(-)μολῶ goes to **ηὐ**τομόλησα in the aorist.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Following Homer's practice, the augment is sometimes not made in poetry, especially epic poetry.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] The augment sometimes substitutes for reduplication; see below.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Almost all forms of the perfect, pluperfect, and future perfect reduplicate the initial syllable of the verb stem.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Irregular duplication can be understood diachronically.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] For example, *lambanō* (root *lab*) has the perfect stem *eilēpha* (not **lelēpha*) because it was originally *slambanō*, with perfect *seslēpha*, becoming *eilēpha* through compensatory lengthening.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Reduplication is also visible in the present tense stems of certain verbs.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] These stems add a syllable consisting of the root's initial consonant followed by *i*.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] A nasal stop appears after the reduplication in some verbs.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] The earliest extant examples of ancient Greek writing (c.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] 1450 BC) are in the syllabic script Linear B.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Beginning in the 8th century BC, however, the Greek alphabet became standard, albeit with some variation among dialects.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Early texts are written in boustrophedon style, but left-to-right became standard during the classic period.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Modern editions of ancient Greek texts are usually written with accents and breathing marks, interword spacing, modern punctuation, and sometimes mixed case, but these were all introduced later.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] The beginning of Apology by Plato exemplifies Attic Greek from the Classical period of ancient Greek.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] How you, men of Athens, are feeling under the power of my accusers, I do not know: actually, even I myself almost forgot who I was because of them, they spoke so persuasively.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] And yet, loosely speaking, nothing they have said is true.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] The study of Ancient Greek in European countries in addition to Latin occupied an important place in the syllabus from the Renaissance until the beginning of the 20th century.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] This was true as well in the United States, where many of the nation's founders received a classically based education.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Latin was emphasized in American colleges, but Greek also was required in the colonial and early national eras, and the study of ancient Greece became increasingly popular in the mid-to-late nineteenth century, the age of American philhellenism.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] In particular, female intellectuals of the era designated the mastering of ancient Greek as essential in becoming a "woman of letters".
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek is still taught as a compulsory or optional subject especially at traditional or elite schools throughout Europe, such as public schools and grammar schools in the United Kingdom.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] In 2006/07, 15,000 pupils studied ancient Greek in Germany according to the Federal Statistical Office of Germany, and 280,000 pupils studied it in Italy.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] It is a compulsory subject alongside Latin in the humanities branch of the Spanish Baccalaureate.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek is taught at most major universities worldwide, often combined with Latin as part of the study of classics.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] In 2010 it was offered in three primary schools in the UK, to boost children's language skills, and was one of seven foreign languages which primary schools could teach 2014 as part of a major drive to boost education standards.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek is taught as a compulsory subject in all gymnasiums and lyceums in Greece.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] It appears to have ceased in 2010, having failed to gain the recognition and acceptance of teachers.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Its first issue appeared in April 2015 as an annex to *Hebdomada Aenigmatum*.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Alfred Rahlfs included a preface, a short history of the Septuagint text, and other front matter translated into ancient Greek in his 1935 edition of the Septuagint; Robert Hanhart also included the introductory remarks to the 2006 revised Rahlfs–Hanhart edition in the language as well.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] *Akropolis World News* reports weekly a summary of the most important news in ancient Greek.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek is also used by organizations and individuals, mainly Greek, who wish to denote their respect, admiration or preference for the use of this language.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] This use is sometimes considered graphical, nationalistic or humorous.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] In any case, the fact that modern Greeks can still wholly or partly understand texts written in non-archaic forms of ancient Greek shows the affinity of the modern Greek language to its ancestral predecessor.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek is often used in the coinage of modern technical terms in the European languages: see English words of Greek origin.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/ancient-greek] Latinized forms of ancient Greek roots are used in many of the scientific names of species and in scientific terminology.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/antecedent-contained-deletion] To understand the issue, it is necessary to understand how VP-ellipsis works.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/antecedent-contained-deletion] In each of these sentences, the VP has been elided in the second half, and the elided VP should be essentially identical to the antecedent in the first clause.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/antecedent-contained-deletion] That is, the missing VP in the first sentence can mean only *wash the dishes*, and in the second sentence, the missing VP can mean only *wash the dishes on Tuesday*.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/antecedent-contained-deletion] read every book that Mary did read every book that Mary did read every book etc.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/antecedent-contained-deletion] Since the elided VP must be essentially identical to its antecedent, and assuming that the antecedent is a full VP, an infinite regress occurs (the subscripted text).
[src:anaphora-linguistics/antecedent-contained-deletion] That is, if we substitute in the antecedent VP into the position of the ellipsis, we must repeat the substitution process ad infinitum.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/antecedent-contained-deletion] The light grey font indicates the elided constituent, i.e. the ellipsis, and the underline marks the antecedent constituent to the ellipsis.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/antecedent-contained-deletion] Since the antecedent constituent contains the ellipsis itself, resolution of the ellipsis necessitates an infinite regress as the antecedent is substituted ad infinitum into the ellipsis site.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/antecedent-contained-deletion] To avoid this problem, Sag (1976) proposed that the NP *every book that Mary did* undergoes *quantifier raising* (QR) to a position above the verb.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/antecedent-contained-deletion] The infinite regress is now avoided because after QR, the antecedent VP contains just the verb *read*.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] In grammar, an **antecedent** is one or more words that identifies a pronoun or other pro-form.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] For example, in the sentence "John arrived late because traffic held him up," the word "John" is the antecedent of the pronoun "him." Pro-forms usually follow their antecedents, but sometimes precede them.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] In the latter case, the more accurate term would technically be *postcedent*, although this term is not commonly distinguished from *antecedent* because the definition of *antecedent* usually encompasses it.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] The linguistic term that is closely related to *antecedent* and *pro-form* is *anaphora*.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] Theories of syntax explore the distinction between antecedents and postcedents in terms of binding.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] Almost any syntactic category can serve as the antecedent to a pro-form.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] The following examples illustrate a range of proforms and their antecedents.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] This list of proforms and the types of antecedents that they take is by no means exhaustive, but rather it is intended to merely deliver an impression of the breadth of expressions that can function as proforms and antecedents.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] While the stereotypical proform is a pronoun and the stereotypical antecedent a noun or noun phrase, these examples demonstrate that most any syntactic category can in fact serve as an antecedent to a proform, whereby the proforms themselves are a diverse bunch.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] The last two examples are particularly interesting, because they show that some proforms can even take discontinuous word combinations as antecedents, i.e. the antecedents are *not* constituents.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] A particularly frequent type of proform occurs in relative clauses.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] Many relative clauses contain a relative pronoun, and these relative pronouns have an antecedent.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] Sentences 'd' and 'h' above contain relative clauses; the proforms *when* and *which* are relative proforms.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] In some cases, the wording could have an uncertain antecedent, where the antecedent of a pronoun is not clear because two or more prior nouns or phrases could match the count, gender, or logic as a prior reference.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] In such cases, scholars have recommended to rewrite the sentence structure to be more specific, or repeat the words of the antecedent rather than use only a pronoun phrase, as a technique to resolve the uncertain antecedent.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] For example, consider the sentence, "There was a doll inside the box that was made of clay", where the word "that" could refer to either the box or the doll.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] Antecedents may also be unclear when they occur far from the noun or phrase they refer to.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] Tyler, “War Imminent as Hussein Rejects Ultimatum,” N.Y.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] As Garner points out, “that were…the border” modifies “messages”, which occurs 7 words (3 of which are nouns) before.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] In context, the phrase could also modify “the Iraqi people”, hence the uncertainty.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] The *ante-* in *antecedent* means 'before; in front of'.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] Thus, when a pro-form precedes its antecedent, the antecedent is not literally an **ante**cedent, but rather it is a **post**cedent, *post-* meaning 'after; behind'.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] Postcedents are rare compared to antecedents, and in practice, the distinction between antecedents and postcedents is often ignored, with the term *antecedent* being used to denote both.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] This practice is a source of confusion, and some have therefore denounced using the term *antecedent* to mean *postcedent* because of this confusion.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] Some pro-forms lack a linguistic antecedent.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] In such cases, the antecedent is implied in the given discourse environment or from general knowledge of the world.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] For instance, the first person pronouns *I*, *me*, *we*, and *us* and the second person pronoun *you* are pro-forms that usually lack a linguistic antecedent.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] However, their antecedents are present in the discourse context as the speaker and the listener.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] Pleonastic pro-forms also lack a linguistic antecedent, e.g.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] *It is raining*, where the pronoun *it* is semantically empty and cannot be viewed as referring to anything specific in the discourse world.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] Definite pro-forms such as *they* and *you* also have an indefinite use, which means they denote some person or people in general, e.g.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/antecedent-grammar] *They will get you for that*, and therefore cannot be construed as taking a linguistic antecedent.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/autonomy-of-syntax] In linguistics, the **autonomy of syntax** is the assumption that syntax is arbitrary and self-contained with respect to meaning: semantics, pragmatics, discourse function, and other factors external to language.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/autonomy-of-syntax] The autonomy of syntax is advocated by linguistic formalists, and in particular by generative linguistics, whose approaches have hence been called ***autonomist linguistics***.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/autonomy-of-syntax] The principle of iconicity is contrasted, for some scenarios, with that of the autonomy of syntax.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/autonomy-of-syntax] The weaker version of the argument for the autonomy of syntax (or that for the autonomy of grammar), includes only for the principle of arbitrariness, while the stronger version includes the claim of self-containedness.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/autonomy-of-syntax] The principle of arbitrariness of syntax is actually accepted by most functionalist linguists, and the real dispute between functionalist and generativists is on the claim of self-containedness of grammar or syntax.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/autonomy-of-syntax] This paralleled the distinction between the two approaches in psychology, behaviorism, which was the dominant approach up until the 1940s, and cognitivism.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/autonomy-of-syntax] Over the decades, multiple instances have been found of cases in which syntactic structures are actually determined or influenced by semantic traits, and some formalists and generativists have reacted to that by shrinking those parts of semantics that they consider autonomous.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/autonomy-of-syntax] Over the decades, in the changes that Noam Chomsky has made to his generative formulation, there has been a shift from a claim for the autonomy of syntax to one for the autonomy of grammar.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/autonomy-of-syntax] The assumption of the autonomy of syntax has been a highly controversial topic in the functionalist and formalist linguistic spheres.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/autonomy-of-syntax] Linguistic functionalists make the argument that semantics play a role in syntax, while linguistic formalists agree that semantics and syntax interact, but they are not affected on each other.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/autonomy-of-syntax] A common example that is used by linguistic formalists to indicate the validity of autonomy in syntax is, "Colorless green ideas sleep furiously", which demonstrates that, in order for a sentence to be syntactically correct, it does not need to be coherent or meaningful in any way.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/autonomy-of-syntax] Various grammar models have been developed both supporting and rejecting the autonomy of syntax.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/autonomy-of-syntax] The main grammatical model that is in support of the Autonomy of Syntax is Generative Grammar, created by Noam Chomsky.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/autonomy-of-syntax] On the other hand, examples of models that argue against it are Construction Grammar, Head-driven Phase Structure Grammar, and Generalized Phase Structure Grammar.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] In linguistics, **binding** is the phenomenon in which anaphoric elements such as pronouns are grammatically associated with their antecedents.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] For instance, in the English sentence "Mary saw herself", the anaphor "herself" is bound by its antecedent "Mary".
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] Binding can be licensed or blocked in certain contexts or syntactic configurations, e.g. the pronoun "her" cannot be bound by "Mary" in the English sentence "Mary saw her".
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] While all languages have binding, restrictions on it vary even among closely related languages.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] Binding has been a major area of research in syntax and semantics since the 1970s and, as the name implies, is a core component of government and binding theory.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] The following sentences illustrate some basic facts of binding.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] The words that bear the index i should be construed as referring to the same person or thing.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] These sentences illustrate some aspects of the distribution of reflexive and personal pronouns.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] In the first pair of sentences, the reflexive pronoun must appear for the indicated reading to be possible.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] In the second pair, the personal pronoun must appear for the indicated reading to be possible.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] The third pair shows that at times a personal pronoun must follow its antecedent, and the fourth pair further illustrates the same point, although the acceptability judgement is not as robust.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] Based on such data, one sees that reflexive and personal pronouns differ in their distribution and that linear order (of a pronoun in relation to its antecedent or postcedent) is a factor influencing where at least some pronouns can appear.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] A theory of binding should be capable of predicting and explaining the differences in distribution seen in sentences like these.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] It should be able to answer questions like: What explains where a reflexive pronoun must appear as opposed to a personal pronoun?
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] When does linear order play a role in determining where pronouns can appear?
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] What other factor (or factors) beyond linear order help predict where pronouns can appear?
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] The following three subsections consider the binding domains that are relevant for the distribution of pronouns and nouns in English.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] The discussion follows the outline provided by the traditional binding theory (see below), which divides nominals into three basic categories: reflexive and reciprocal pronouns, personal pronouns, and nouns (common and proper).
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] When one examines the distribution of reflexive pronouns and reciprocal pronouns (which are often subsumed under the general category of "anaphor"), one sees that there are certain domains that are relevant, a "domain" being a syntactic unit that is clause-like.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] Reflexive and reciprocal pronouns often seek their antecedent close by, in a binding domain that is local, e.g.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] These examples illustrate that there is a domain within which a reflexive or reciprocal pronoun should find its antecedent.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] The a-sentences are fine because the reflexive or reciprocal pronoun has its antecedent within the clause.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] The b-sentences, in contrast, do not allow the indicated reading, a fact illustrating that personal pronouns have a distribution that is different from that of reflexive and reciprocal pronouns.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] A related observation is that a reflexive and reciprocal pronoun often cannot seek its antecedent in a superordinate clause, e.g.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] When the reflexive or reciprocal pronoun attempts to find an antecedent outside of the immediate clause containing it, it fails.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] In other words, it can hardly seek its antecedent in the superordinate clause.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] The binding domain that is relevant is the immediate clause containing it.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] Personal pronouns have a distribution that is different from reflexive and reciprocal pronouns, a point that is evident with the first two b-sentences in the previous section.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] The local binding domain that is decisive for the distribution of reflexive and reciprocal pronouns is also decisive for personal pronouns, but in a different way.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] Personal pronouns seek their antecedent outside of the local binding domain containing them, e.g.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] In these cases, the pronoun has to look outside of the embedded clause containing it to the matrix clause to find its antecedent.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] Hence based on such data, the relevant binding domain appears to be the clause.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] Since the pronouns appear within the same minimal clause containing their antecedents in these cases, one cannot argue that the relevant binding domain is the clause.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] The most one can say based on such data is that the domain is "clause-like".
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] The distribution of common and proper nouns is unlike that of reflexive, reciprocal, and personal pronouns.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] The relevant observation in this regard is that a noun is often reluctantly coreferential with another nominal that is within its binding domain or in a superordinate binding domain, e.g.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] The readings indicated in the a-sentences are natural, whereas the b-sentences are very unusual.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] Indeed, sentences like these b-sentences were judged to be impossible in the traditional binding theory according to Condition C (see below).
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] Given a contrastive context, however, the b-sentences can work, e.g.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] *Susan does not admire Jane, but rather Susani admires Susani*.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] One can therefore conclude that nouns are not sensitive to binding domains in the same way that reflexive, reciprocal, and personal pronouns are.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] The following subsections illustrate the extent to which pure linear order impacts the distribution of pronouns.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] While linear order is clearly important, it is not the only factor influencing where pronouns can appear.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] A simple hypothesis concerning the distribution of many anaphoric elements, of personal pronouns in particular, is that linear order plays a role.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] In most cases, a pronoun follows its antecedent, and in many cases, the coreferential reading is impossible if the pronoun precedes its antecedent.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] While the coreferential readings indicated in these b-sentences are possible, they are unlikely.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] The order presented in the a-sentences is strongly preferred.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] While the acceptability judgements here are nuanced, one can make a strong case that pure linear order is at least in part predictive of when the indicated reading is available.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] The a- and c-sentences allow the coreferential reading more easily than their b- and d-counterparts.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] While linear order is an important factor influencing the distribution of pronouns, it is not the only factor.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] The following sentences are similar to the c- and d-sentences in the previous section insofar as an embedded clause is present.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] While there may be a mild preference for the order in the a-sentences here, the indicated reading in the b-sentences is also available.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] Hence linear order is hardly playing a role in such cases.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] The relevant difference between these sentences and the c- and d-sentences in the previous section is that the embedded clauses here are adjunct clauses, whereas they are argument clauses above.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] The fact that the c-sentences marginally allow the indicated reading whereas the b-sentences do not at all allow this reading further demonstrates that linear order is important.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] But in this regard, the d-sentences are telling, since if linear order were the entire story, one would expect the d-sentences to be less acceptable than they are.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] The conclusion that one can draw from such data is that there are one or more other factors beyond linear order that are impacting the distribution of pronouns.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] Given that linear order is not the only factor influencing the distribution of pronouns, the question is what other factor or factors might also be playing a role.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] The traditional binding theory (see below) took c-command to be the all-important factor, but the importance of c-command for syntactic theorizing has been extensively criticized in recent years.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] The primary alternative to c-command is functional rank.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] These two competing concepts (c-command vs. rank) have been debated extensively and they continue to be debated.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] C-command is a configurational notion; it is defined over concrete syntactic configurations.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] Syntactic rank, in contrast, is a functional notion that resides in the lexicon; it is defined over the ranking of the arguments of predicates.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] Subjects are ranked higher than objects, first objects are ranked higher than second objects, and prepositional objects are ranked lowest.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] The following two subsections briefly consider these competing notions.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] C-command is a configurational notion that acknowledges the syntactic configuration as primitive.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] Basic subject-object asymmetries, which are numerous in many languages, are explained by the fact that the subject appears outside of the finite verb phrase (VP) constituent, whereas the object appears inside it.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] Subjects therefore c-command objects, but not vice versa.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] Node A c-commands node B if every node dominating A also dominates B, and neither A nor B dominates the other.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] Given the binary division of the clause (S → NP + VP) associated with most phrase structure grammars, this definition sees a typical subject c-commanding everything inside the verb phrase (VP), whereas everything inside the VP is incapable of c-commanding anything outside of the VP.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] Some basic binding facts are explained in this manner, e.g.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] Sentence a is fine because the subject *Larry* c-commands the object *himself*, whereas sentence b does not work because the object *Larry* does not c-command the subject *himself*.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] The assumption has been that within its binding domain, a reflexive pronoun must be c-commanded by its antecedent.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] While this approach based on c-command makes a correct prediction much of the time, there are other cases where it fails to make the correct prediction, e.g.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] The reading indicated is acceptable in this case, but if c-command were the key notion helping to explain where the reflexive can and must appear, then the reading should be impossible since *himself* is not c-commanded by *Larry*.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] As reflexive and personal pronouns occur in complementary distribution, the notion of c-command can also be used to explain where personal pronouns can appear.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] The assumption is that personal pronouns *cannot* c-command their antecedent, e.g.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] In both examples, the personal pronoun *she* does not c-command its antecedent *Alice*, resulting in the grammaticality of both sentences despite reversed linear order.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] The alternative to a c-command approach posits a ranking of syntactic functions (SUBJECT > FIRST OBJECT > SECOND OBJECT > PREPOSITIONAL OBJECT).
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] Subject-object asymmetries are addressed in terms of this ranking.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] Since subjects are ranked higher than objects, an object can have the subject as its antecedent, but not vice versa.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] With basic cases, this approach makes the same prediction as the c-command approach.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] Since the subject outranks the object, sentence a is predictably acceptable, the subject *Larry* outranking the object *himself*.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] Sentence b, in contrast, is bad because the subject reflexive pronoun *himself* outranks its postcedent *Larry*.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] In other words, this approach in terms of rank is assuming that within its binding domain, a reflexive pronoun may not outrank its antecedent (or postcedent).
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] The approach based on rank does not require a particular configurational relationship to hold between a reflexive pronoun and its antecedent.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] In other words, it makes no prediction in this case, and hence does not make an incorrect prediction.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] The reflexive pronoun *himself* is embedded within the subject noun phrase, which means that it is not the subject and hence does not outrank the object *Larry*.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] A theory of binding that acknowledges both linear order and rank can at least begin to predict many of the marginal readings.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] When both linear order and rank combine, acceptability judgments are robust, e.g.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] – Linear order and rank combine to make the indicated reading easily possible.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] – Linear order and rank combine to make the indicated reading impossible.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] – Linear order alone makes the indicated reading possible; rank is not involved.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] – Linear order alone makes the indicated reading unlikely; rank is not involved.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] This ability to address marginal readings is something that an approach combining linear order and rank can accomplish, whereas an approach that acknowledges only c-command cannot do the same.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] The exploration of binding phenomena began in the 1970s and interest peaked in the 1980s with Government and Binding Theory, a grammar framework in the tradition of generative syntax that is still prominent today.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] The theory of binding that became widespread at that time serves now merely as reference point (since it is no longer believed to be correct).
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] This theory distinguishes between 3 different binding conditions: A, B, and C.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] The theory classifies nominals according to two features, [±anaphor] and [±pronominal], which are binary.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] The binding characteristics of a nominal are determined by the values of these features, either plus or minus.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] Thus, a nominal that is [-anaphor, -pronominal] is an R-expression (referring expression), such as a common noun or a proper name.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] A nominal that is [-anaphor, +pronominal] is a pronoun, such as *he* or *they*, and a nominal that is [+anaphor, -pronominal] is a reflexive pronoun, such as *himself* or *themselves*.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] Note that the term *anaphor* here is being used in a specialized sense; it essentially means "reflexive".
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] This meaning is specific to the Government and Binding framework and has not spread beyond this framework.
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] An anaphor (reflexive) must be locally bound (have a local (nearby) antecedent).
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] A pronoun must not be locally bound (can have an antecedent as long as the antecedent is not local or does not c-command the pronoun).
[src:anaphora-linguistics/binding-linguistics] It cannot corefer with anything that c-commands it.
